Twenty years since this album dropped and I picked it up at the Best Buy in Downers Grove, IL with money made from being the single worst babysitter in the southwest suburbs. At the time it was vexing: Could this new Liz Phair, with her gigantic hooks and pop whimsy, be the same wise cynic who blessed us with Exile In Guyville ten years earlier? I felt this was most confounding to people who weren’t really paying attention to Liz. She always delivered a bunch of personal layers at once — the optimism, the disappointment, the humor, the horror, the whatever. If anything made me feel “seen” as a young adult, it was how artists like her embraced those juxtapositions, and this album felt to me like a wild and in some ways more vulnerable addition to her previous work. I’ll always associate this album with my best summer memories (and my ensuing coming-out) and now that I’m the exact age she was when she released it, I’m singing “Rock Me” and “Why Can’t I” in my car with what I’ll call *earned wisdom*. "Friend of Mine" and "Jeremy Engle" (from the bonus EP comeandgetit) are my favorite deep cuts. Always Liz, forever.
